Paste this in (Tell him to replace yourdomain.com with his actual domain or IP):

Nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name yourdomain.com;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:3000; # This points to your Node.js app
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header Connection 'upgrade';
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
    }
}
Save and Exit (Ctrl+O, Enter, Ctrl+X).

Link the file and restart Nginx:

Bash
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/firetech /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl restart nginx
Step 3: Get the SSL Certificate (The "HTTPS" part)
We use Certbot (from Let's Encrypt) to get the certificate for free.

Bash
sudo apt install -y certbot python3-certbot-nginx
sudo certbot --nginx -d yourdomain.com
Certbot will ask for an email and then automatically update the Nginx file to enable HTTPS.

Important: Local vs. Public
If he is on a Local Network: You cannot easily get a "Real" HTTPS certificate for a local IP (like 192.168...). He would have to use a Self-Signed Certificate, but the browser will show a "Danger" warning.

If he is Public: He must have a domain name pointed to his IP address for the script above to work.

